{"parse":{"title":"flower","pageid":4561,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Flower}}\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n[[Image:Cactus in Bloom 01.jpg|thumb|Pink cactus flowers in bloom.]]\n{{picdic\n|image=Flor.png\n|detail1=\n{{picdicimg|en|image=Brunfelsia pauciflora shrub.jpg|link=plant}}\n|detail2=\n'''Legend:'''<br/>\n1= [[style#English|style]]\n2= [[ovary#English|ovary]]\n3= [[receptaculum#English|receptaculum]]<br>\n4= [[stamen#English|stamen]]\n5= [[petal#English|petal]]\n6= [[stigma#English|stigma]]<br>\n7= [[pistil#English|pistil]]\n8= [[sepal#English|sepal]]\n9= [[pedicel#English|pedicel]]\n|detail3=\nSome flowers:\n{{picdicimg|en|image=Narcissus.calcicola.7114.jpg|link=daffodil}}\n{{picdicimg|en|image=Dahlia - roze.jpg|link=dahlia}}\n{{picdicimg|en|image=LiliumBulbiferumCroceumBologna.jpg|link=lily}}\n{{picdicimg|en|image=Nerium oleander September 2007-1.jpg|link=oleander}}\n{{picdicimg|en|image=Red rose.jpg|link=rose}}\n{{picdicimg|en|image=Tulipa suaveolens floriade to Canberra.jpg|link=tulip}}\n|scrollable=yes\n}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|en|flowre||obsolete}}\n* {{alt|en|flow'r||[[archaic]] or [[poetic]]}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*bʰleh₃-}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|flour}}, from {{der|en|xno|flur}}, from {{der|en|la|flōrem}}, accusative of {{m|la|flōs}}, from {{der|en|itc-pro|*flōs}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bʰleh₃-||to thrive, bloom}}. {{doublet|en|fleur|flor|flour|bloom|blossom}}.\n\nPartly displaced native {{cog|ang|blostma}} (which is cognate), whence {{w|Modern English}} {{m|en|blossom}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{a|en|non-rhotic}}\n** {{a|en|UK}}\n*** {{IPA|en|/ˈflaʊ̯.əː/|[ˈflaʊ̯.əː]|a=RP}}\n**** {{audio|en|en-uk-flower.ogg}}\n*** {{IPA|en|/ˈfluː.ɐ/|[ˈfluː.ɐ]|a=Northumbria}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈflæʊ̯.əː/|[ˈflæʊ̯.əː]|a=AU,NZ,[[w:Fronting (sound change)|/aʊ̯/-fronting]]}}\n*** {{audio|en|en-au-flower.ogg}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈflaː.əː/|[ˈflaː.əː]|a=ZA,[[w:monopthongization|/aʊ̯/-monopthongization]]}}\n* {{a|en|rhotic}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈflaʊ̯.ɚ/|[ˈflaʊ̯.ɚ]|~|[ˈflaʊ̯.ɹ̩]|a=GA,[[w:Standard Canadian English|Standard Canadian]]}}\n*** {{audio|en|en-us-flower.ogg}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈflæʊ̯.ɚ/|[ˈflæʊ̯.ɚ]|~|[ˈflæʊ̯.ɹ̩]|a=Southern US,Midland US,Mid-Atlantic US,NYC,[[w:Fronting (sound change)|/aʊ̯/-fronting]]}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈflaː.ɚ/|[ˈflaː.ɚ]|~|[ˈflaː.ɹ̩]|a=Pittsburgh,[[w:monopthongization|/aʊ̯/-monopthongization]]}}\n* {{a|en|Indic}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈflaː(r)/|[ˈflaː(r)]|;|/ˈflɐ.ʋə(r)/|[ˈflɐ.ʋə(r)]|;|/ˈflɐ.wə(r)/|[ˈflɐ.wə(r)]|a=India}}\n* {{rhymes|en|aʊ.ə(ɹ)|s1=2}}\n* {{hyph|en|flow|er}}\n* {{homophones|en|flour|aa1=for people who pronounce ''flower'' as one syllable, or ''flour'' as two}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# A [[colorful]], [[conspicuous]] [[structure#Noun|structure]] [[associate#Verb|associated]] with [[angiosperm]]s, frequently [[scented#Adjective|scented]] and [[attract]]ing various [[insect]]s, and which may or may not be used for [[sexual reproduction]].\n#* {{RQ:Basse Pastorals|poem=Clio, or The First Muse; in 9 Eglogues in Honor of 9 Vertues. As It was in His Dayes Intended. [Munday. Laurinella. Eglogue. Of True and Chast Love.]|passage=O Laurinella! little doſt thou wot / How fraile a '''flower''' thou doſt ſo highly prize: / Beauty's the '''flower''', but love the '''flower'''-pot / That muſt preſerve it, els it quickly dyes.}}\n#* {{RQ:Tolkien Fellowship of the Ring|chapter=A Long-Expected Party|passage= The '''flowers''' glowed red and golden: snapdragons and sunflowers, and nasturtians trailing all over the turf walls and peeping in at the round windows.}}\n# {{senseid|en|Q506}}{{lb|en|botany}} A [[reproductive]] structure in [[angiosperm]]s (flowering plants), often conspicuously colourful and typically including [[sepal]]s, [[petal]]s, and either or both [[stamen]]s and/or a [[pistil]].\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1894|author=w:H. G. Wells|title=s:The Flowering of the Strange Orchid\n|passage=You know, Darwin studied their fertilisation, and showed that the whole structure of an ordinary orchid '''flower''' was contrived in order that moths might carry the pollen from plant to plant.}}\n# {{senseid|en|flower-bearing plant}} A [[plant]] that bears flowers, especially a plant that is small and lacks [[wood]].\n#: {{ux|en|We transplanted the '''flowers''' to a larger pot.}}\n# The [[stem]] of a flowering plant with the blossom or blossoms attached, used for decoration, as a gift, etc.\n#: {{ux|en|He always keeps a vase full of '''flowers''' in his office.}}\n# {{lb|en|uncountable|usually with ''in''}} Of plants, a state of bearing [[bloom]]s.\n#: {{ux|en|The dogwoods are in '''flower''' this week.}}\n# {{lb|en|euphemistic|hypocoristic}} The [[vulva]], especially the [[labia majora]].\n#* {{RQ:Cleland Fanny Hill|letter=I|page=106|passage=[F]or ſtill, that my virgin-'''flower''' was yet uncrop'd never once enter'd into his head, and he would have thought it idling with time and words to have queſtion'd me upon it.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1893| title=The Voice of a Flower |author=Emily Gerard | page=44| passage=So was it asserted, that whenever a maiden was destined to die unmarried, as surely would the plant wither away and perish, and if a dughter of the Renseccos lost her honour or had given away her '''flower''' to an unworthy lover, then would the flower be blighted overnight.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2018| title=Gender, Violence and Attitudes: Lessons from Early Modern Europe|author=Satu Lidman | page=| passage=In some local tradditions a fallen bride was married wearing a crown of straw rather than a garland of flowers, to symbolize her loss of  virginity – the wilting of her '''flower'''. }}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2019| title=Mage Against the Machine |author=Shaun Barger | page=146| passage=\"Our flesh as one!\" he laughed, speaking loudly. \"Sweating bodies entwined in carnal passion! As I plunge myself ''deep'' into her lady '''flower''', again and again and again— !\"}}\n# The [[best]] examples or representatives of a group.\n#* {{RQ:Skelton Complete|Scottes|116|lines=25–28|At {{w|Battle of Flodden|Floddon hyllys}}, / Our bowys, our byllys / Slew all the '''floure''' / Of theyr honoure.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1597 [1593–1662]|author=[[Richard Hooker]]|title= Of the Lawes of Ecclesiastical Politie|url=https://archive.org/details/gri_ofthelawesof00hook/page/258/mode/2up|chapter=The fifth Booke|page=258|passage=The choice and [[flower]] of all things profitable in other Bookes, the Pſalmes doe both more briefly contayne, and more mouingly alſo expreſſe, by reason of that Poeticall forme wherewith they are written.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1808|author=w:Robert Southey|title=Chronicle of the Cid, from the Spanish\n|passage=the '''flower''' of the chivalry of all Spain}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1915|author=Katharine Tynan|title=The Golden Boy\n|passage=In times of peace, so clean and bright, / And with a new-washed morning face, / He walked Pall Mall, a goodly sight, / The finished '''flower''' of all the race.}}\n# The [[best]] state of things; the [[prime]].\n#: {{ux|en|She was in the '''flower''' of her life.}}\n#* {{RQ:Tennyson Poems 1842|volume=I|poem=Lady Clara Vere de Vere|stanza=2|page=156|passage=A simple maiden in her '''flower''' / Is worth a hundred coats-of-arms.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=[[w:James Mackintosh Kennedy|James [Mackintosh] Kennedy]]|chapter=To Queen Alexandra|title=The Scottish and American Poems of James Kennedy|publisher=[[w:J. S. Ogilvie|J[ohn] S[tuart] Ogilvie]] Publishing Company,{{nb...|57 Rose Street}}|year=1899|page=197|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/scottishandameri00kenniala/page/197/mode/1up|passage=NO lady fair in hall or bower, / In days when knighthood was in '''flower''', / Or high-born dame with jewels set, / Or Tudor or Plantagenet, / E’er wore enwreath’d on form and face / Thy royal robe of richest grace.}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[flour|Flour]].\n#* {{RQ:Arbuthnot Aliments|chapter=Of the Different Intentions to be Pursued in the Choice of Aliment in Different Constitutions|prop=VII|page=185|passage=The '''Flovvers''' of Grains mix'd vvith VVater vvill make a ſort of Glue.}}\n# {{senseid|en|sublimed powder}}{{lb|en|in the plural|chemistry|obsolete}} A substance in the form of a [[powder]], especially when [[condense]]d from [[sublimation]].\n#: {{ux|en|the '''flowers''' of sulphur}}\n#* {{RQ:Boyle Sceptical Chymist|passage=Exposed to a moderate fire in subliming pots, [brimstone] rises all into dry, and almost tasteless, '''flowers'''; whereas being exposed to a naked fire, it affords store of a saline and fretting liquor.}}\n# A [[figure of speech]]; an [[ornament]] of [[style]].\n# {{lb|en|printing}} Ornamental [[type]] used chiefly for borders around pages, cards, etc.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1841|author=William Savage|title=A Dictionary of the Art of Printing\n|passage=I pointed out to the late Mr. Catherwood, of the firm of Caslon and Catherwood, the inconvenience of both these modes of cutting '''flowers''',}}\n# {{lb|en|in the plural|obsolete}} [[menstrual|Menstrual]] [[discharge]]s.\n#* {{RQ:King James Version|Leviticus|15|24|passage=And if any man lye with her at all, and her '''flowers''' be vpon him, hee shall be vncleane seuen dayes: and all the bed whereon he lyeth, shall be vncleane.}}\n# A [[delicate]], [[fragile]]{{,}} or [[oversensitive]] person.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2015|author=Sally Chiwuzie|title=Silent Symphonies\n|passage={{...}} she whispered leaning over and kissing her forehead; and then added, 'Mummy loves you, precious '''flower'''.'}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2016|author=Barbara Ann Wright|title=Paladins of the Storm Lord\n|passage=“Take care of yourself out there, Brown, you delicate '''flower'''.”}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2021|author=Alica McKenna-Johnson|title=The Unicorn's Scion\n|passage=“Come on, you delicate '''flower''', we just need to nap. It will be fine.”}}\n# {{lb|en|figurative|chiefly|in the plural}} [[credit|Credit]], [[recognition]].\n#: {{ux|en|to give someone his '''flowers''';&emsp;to get one's '''flowers'''}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2010| title=A Tribute to 101 Incredible Women of Distinction Who Influenced My Life From My House to the White House|author=M. Joyce Dickerson | page=| passage=It has been my desire to find a way to express my gratitude to these women for quite some time but I really did not know how to give them their '''flowers''' as a method to tell them thanks.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2011| title=Game of My Life Alabama Crimson Tide|author=Tommy Hicks | page=149| passage=I was able to give Coach Bryant his '''flowers''' while he was alive, and I have always been thankful I was able to do that.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2023| title=Alpha's Unexpected Luna|author=Torry Smith | page=| passage=Gonzalo managed to fake a smile. When will anyone ever give him his '''flowers'''? His hard work kept him and his kingdom this far. Wasn't anyone going to acknowledge the fact?}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2024-09-21|author=Heath Owens|title=What to Wear to Sabrina Carpenter's 'Short N' Sweet' Tour|journal=w:[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/style-beauty/fashion/a62289922/what-to-wear-to-sabrina-carpenter-concert-short-n-sweet-tour/|passage={{w|Sabrina Carpenter}} is, ''finally'', getting her '''flowers'''. Ever since demurely (I don't use that word lightly!!!) performing what would become the song of 2024 as part of her Coachella set—no, literally, \"{{w|Espresso (song)|Espresso}}\" just won the {{w|MTV Video Music Award for Song of the Year}}—all eyes have been on 'Brina.}}\n# {{lb|en|uncountable|slang}} [[cannabis|Cannabis]].\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* In its most common sense as \"a colorful conspicuous structure\", the word ''flower'' includes many structures which are not anatomically flowers in the botanical sense. Sunflowers and daisies, for example, are structurally clusters of many small flowers that together appear to be a single flower (a {{m|en|capitulum}}, a form of {{m|en|pseudanthium}}), but these are considered to be ''flowers'' in the general sense. Likewise, the botanical definition of ''flower'' includes many structures that would not be considered a flower by the average person, such as the [[catkin]]s of a willow tree or the downy flowers found atop a [[cattail]] stalk.\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|inflorescence that resembles a flower}} {{l|en|head}}, {{l|en|pseudanthium}}\n* {{sense|best examples}} {{l|en|cream}}\n* {{sense|best state of things}} {{l|en|prime}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|animal flower\n|arcigera flower moth\n|Bach flower remedy|equinox flower\n|Bach flower therapy\n|ball-flower,ball flower\n|balloon flower\n|basketflower\n|bat flower|flower of life|skeleton flower\n|beflower|revolver flower\n|bellflower\n|Bill Gates' flower fly\n|blanketflower\n|blanket flower\n|bone-eating snot flower worm\n|bunchflower\n|burst into flower|breeches-flower|porcupine flower|prison flower\n|butter flower|flower cluster|side-saddle flower\n|cardinal flower\n|carrion flower|flower-smoke\n|Chihuahua flower|Indian trumpet flower|chocolate flower\n|Christmas flower|popcorn flower|troll-flower|Venus' flower basket\n|composite flower\n|coneflower,cone flower,cone-flower\n|corkscrew flower\n|cornflower\n|crowflower\n|crown flower\n|cuckooflower\n|cupflower\n|dayflower|flower stem|pinwheel flower|princess flower|Easter flower\n|egg flower soup\n|elderflower\n|electric flower car\n|enflower\n|everlasting flower\n|fanflower\n|fennel-flower\n|fennelflower\n|Fine Flower\n|firecracker flower\n|flameflower\n|flamingo flower\n|flannel flower\n|flowerage|bone-eating snot flower|printers' flower|tumbling flower beetle\n|flower arrangement|spider flower\n|flower-bearing\n|flower bed\n|flower beetle\n|flower bond\n|flower box\n|flower bug\n|flower car\n|flower chafer\n|flower child\n|flower clock\n|flower crown\n|flower delice,flower-de-luce,flower deluce\n|flowerer\n|flower-fence\n|flower-fly\n|flower fly\n|flowerful\n|flower garden\n|flower-gentle\n|flower head\n|flower hoe\n|flowerhorn\n|flowerkind\n|flowerless\n|flowerlet\n|flowerlike\n|flower longhorn\n|flowerly\n|flower mantis\n|flower moon\n|flower moth\n|Flower Mound\n|flowerness\n|flower-of-an-hour\n|flower of Jove\n|flower of the flock\n|flowerpecker\n|flower-petal,flower petal\n|flowerpicking\n|flowerpiece\n|flowerpiercer\n|flower power\n|flower service\n|flower sticks\n|flower-strewn\n|flower-sweet\n|flower wall\n|flower water\n|flower weevil\n|foamflower\n|four-o'clock flower,four o'clock flower\n|frost flower\n|gallflower,gall flower\n|ghostflower\n|gilli-flower,gilly-flower\n|globeflower\n|handflower\n|honey flower\n|hothouse flower\n|incomplete flower\n|in flower\n|inside-out flower\n|in the flower of one's youth\n|Joseph's flower\n|July-flower\n|laceflower\n|lantern flower\n|largeflower\n|leopard flower\n|luxuriant flower\n|mayflower\n|mistflower\n|moccasin flower\n|monkey-flower\n|monkeyflower\n|moonflower\n|muskflower\n|nanoflower\n|noonflower,noon-flower\n|overflower\n|pagoda flower\n|paperflower\n|paper flower\n|paschal flower\n|pasque flower\n|Passionflower,Passion flower,passion-flower,passion flower\n|Paul Allen's flower fly\n|peacock flower\n|pelican flower\n|pencil flower\n|pineapple flower\n|pinkster flower\n|polyflower\n|pompon flower\n|preflower\n|prickly chaff flower\n|pseudoflower\n|red cardinal flower\n|Redflower\n|red flower\n|red princess flower\n|reflower\n|rice flower\n|Rogation-flower\n|satinflower\n|savanna flower\n|savannah flower\n|shellflower\n|shoe flower\n|skyflower\n|sleep-flower,sleep flower\n|slipper flower\n|snailflower\n|spoonflower\n|spurflower\n|starfish flower\n|starflower\n|state flower\n|strawflower\n|sulphurflower\n|tiger flower\n|treasure flower\n|trigger flower\n|trumpet flower\n|Tudor flower\n|twinflower\n|unflower\n|united flower\n|upflower\n|velvet flower\n|Venus's flower basket\n|wall flower\n|wallflower,wall-flower|brimstone flower|orange flower water\n|wax flower\n|waxflower\n|windflower\n|wishbone flower\n|wood-shaving flower\n}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|reproductive structure in angiosperms}}\n{{multitrans|data=\n* Abkhaz: {{t|ab|ашәҭ}}\n* Acehnese: {{t|ace|bungong}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|blom}}\n* Ainu: {{t|ain|エプィケ|tr=epuyke}},  {{t|ain|エプィゲ|tr=epuyge}},  {{t|ain|トㇺ|tr=tom}},  {{t|ain|ノンノ|tr=nonno}}\n* Akkadian: {{t|akk|𒄧|tr=inbum}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|lule|f}}\n* Altai:\n*: Northern Altai: {{t|atv|чеджек}}, {{t|atv|дьакайак}}, {{t|atv|чакайак}}\n*: Southern Altai: {{t|alt|чечек}}\n* Amharic: {{t|am|አበባ}}\n* Ao: {{t|njo|naro}} {{q|Chungli}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|زَهْرَة|f}},  {{t|ar|زُهُور|p}},  {{t|ar|أَزْهَار|p}},  {{t|ar|وَرْدَة|f}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{t|arz|وَرد|m|tr=ward}} {{qualifier|collective}},  {{t|arz|وَرْدَة|f|tr=warda}} (''[[singulative]]'')\n* Aragonese: {{t|an|flor|f}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Syriac: {{t|arc|ܗܒܒܐ|tr=habbāḇāʾ|m}},  {{t|arc|ܗܒܬܐ|tr=habb(ə)ṯāʾ|f}}\n* Archi: {{t|aqc|тӏеӏ}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|ծաղիկ}}\n* Aromanian: {{t|rup|floari|f}},  {{t|rup|floarã|f}},  {{t+|rup|floare|f}},  {{t|rup|lilici|f}},  {{t+|rup|lilice|f}},  {{t|rup|lãludã|f}}\n* Assamese: {{t|as|ফুল}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|flor|f}}\n* Aukan: {{t|djk|boomiki}}\n* Avar: {{t|av|тӏе}},  {{t|av|тӏегь}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t+|az|çiçək}}\n* Baluchi: {{t|bal|پل|tr=pull}}\n* Bashkir: {{t|ba|сәскә}}\n* Basque: {{t+|eu|lore}},  {{t|eu|lili}}\n* Bats: {{t|bbl|ბუბუკ}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|кве́тка|f}}\n* Bengali: {{t+|bn|ফুল}}\n* Bhojpuri: {{t|bho|ফুল|tr=phul}}\n* Bikol:\n*: Central Bikol: {{t+|bcl|burak}}\n* Bole: {{t|bol|bitte}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|bleuñv}} {{qualifier|collective}},  {{t|br|bleuñvienn|f}},  {{t+|br|bleunienn|f}},  {{t+|br|boked|m}}, [[fleur]] {{qualifier|collective}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|цве́те|m}}\n* Burmese: {{t+|my|ပန်း}}\n* Buryat: {{t|bua|сэсэг}}\n* Carpathian Rusyn: {{t|rue|цві́тя}},  {{t|rue|цві́ток|m}},  {{t|rue|цві́тка|f}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|flor|f}}\n* Cebuano: {{t|ceb|bulak}}\n* Central Atlas Tamazight: {{t|tzm|ⴰⵊⴷ