t|tk|gül}}\n* Udmurt: {{t|udm|сяська}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|кві́тка|f}},  {{t+|uk|цвіт|m}}\n* Unami: {{t|unm|òtaès}}\n* Urdu: {{t|ur|پُھول|m}},  {{t|ur|پُشْپ|m}} {{qualifier|rare}}\n* Uyghur: {{t+|ug|گۈل}},  {{t|ug|چېچەك}}\n* Uzbek: {{t+|uz|chechak}},  {{t+|uz|gul}}\n* Venetan: {{t+|vec|fior}}\n* Veps: {{t|vep|änik}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|hoa}} ( {{t+|vi|花}}),  {{t+|vi|bông}}\n* Volapük: {{t+|vo|flor}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|fleur}}\n* Welsh: {{t+|cy|blodyn|m}}\n* Wolaytta: {{t|wal|ciishshaa}}\n* Wolof: {{t|wo|ntortor}}\n* Wutunhua: {{t|wuh|maidok}},  {{t|wuh|hu}}\n* Xhosa: {{t|xh|intyatyambo}}\n* Yaghnobi: {{t|yai|гул}}\n* Yakan: {{t|yka|sumping}}\n* Yakut: {{t|sah|чэчик}},  {{t|sah|сибэкки}}\n* Yao (Africa): {{t|yao|liluŵa|5}}\n* Yiddish: {{t|yi|בלום|f}},  {{t|yi|קווייט|m}}\n* Yoruba: {{t|yo|òdòdó}}\n* Yucatec Maya: {{t|yua|lool}},  {{t|yua|nikte’}}\n* Zealandic: {{t|zea|blomme|f}}\n* Zhuang: {{t|za|va}}\n* Zulu: {{t|zu|imbali|c9|c10}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|plant that bears flowers, especially a plant that is small and lacks wood}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|ծաղիկ}}\n* Bashkir: {{t|ba|сәскә}},  {{t|ba|гөл}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|цве́те|n}}\n* Buryat: {{t|bua|сэсэг}}, {{t|bua|сэсэгтэ ургамал}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|květina|f}}\n* Estonian: {{t+|et|lill}}\n* Farefare: {{t|gur|puugo}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kukka}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Blume|f}}\n* Hmong:\n*: White Hmong: {{t|mww|paj}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|гүл}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|цвето́к|m}}\n* Tzotzil: {{t|tzo|nichim}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|кві́тка|f}}\n}}<!-- close multitrans -->\n{{trans-bottom}}\n{{trans-top|best examples of a group}}\n* Middle English: {{t|enm|blome|id=bloom}}, {{t|enm|flour}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lbl|en|intransitive}} To put forth [[bloom]]s.\n#: {{ux|en|This plant '''flowers''' in June.}}\n# {{lbl|en|transitive}} To decorate with pictures of flowers.\n# {{lbl|en|intransitive}} To reach a state of full [[development]] or achievement.\n#* {{RQ:Spenser Shepheardes Calender|December|year=1586|text=when '''flowr'd''' my youthful spring}}\n#* '''1940''' {{w|Mahadev Desai}}, translator, {{w|Mahatma Gandhi}}, ''An Autobiography'', Part III (IX) The Story of My Experiments with Truth/Part III/Simple Life, original published 1927-1929\n#*: It only needed watering to take root, to '''flower''' and to fructify, and the watering came in due course.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2012|author=Naomi Wolf|title=Vagina: A New Biography|page=43\n|passage=In life after life of this now-expanded circle of women artists, writers and revolutionaries, the same appeared: a flowing of creative insight and vision seemed the follow a sexual '''flowering'''.}}\n# {{lbl|en|archaic|intransitive}} To froth; to ferment gently, as new beer.\n#* {{RQ:Bacon Sylva Sylvarum|passage=That beer did '''flower''' a little.}}\n# {{lbl|en|intransitive}} To come off as flowers by [[sublimation]].\n#* {{RQ:Milton Of Education|passage=observations which have '''flowered''' off}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|to put forth blooms}} {{l|en|bloom}}, {{l|en|blossom}}\n* {{sense|reach a state of achievement}} {{l|en|flourish}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|en|flowering ash|flowering desert|flowering dogwood|flowering plant|flowering rush|flowering tea|night-flowering jasmine}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|to put forth blooms}}\n{{multitrans|data=\n* Amharic: {{t|am|አበበ}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|أَزْهَرَ}},  {{t|ar|إِزْدَهَرَ}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|ծաղկել}}\n* Aromanian: {{t|rup|nflurescu}}\n* Asturian: {{t|ast|florecer}}\n* Bashkir: {{t|ba|сәскә атыу}}\n* Bikol:\n*: Central Bikol: {{t|bcl|mamurak}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|bleuniañ}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|цъфтя}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|florir}}\n* Cherokee: {{t|chr|ᎠᏥᎸᏍᎦ}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t|yue|開花|tr=hoi1 faa1}}\n*: Hakka: {{t|hak|開花|tr=khôi-fâ}}\n*: Hokkien: {{t|nan-hbl|開花|tr=khui-hoe}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|開花|tr=kāihuā}}\n* Cornish: {{t|kw|bleujyowa}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|kvést}}\n* Dalmatian: {{t|dlm|inflorer}}\n* Danish: {{t|da|blomstre}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|bloeien}},  {{t+|nl|openbloeien}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|flori}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kukkia}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|fleurir}},  {{t+|fr|s'épanouir}}\n* Friulian: {{t|fur|florî}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|florecer}},  {{t|gl|choridar}},  {{t|gl|churir}},  {{t|gl|esbrochar}},  {{t+|gl|rosear}},  {{t+|gl|recandear}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|აყვავება}},  {{t|ka|აყვავილება}}\n* German: {{t+|de|blühen}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|ανθώ}},  {{t+|el|ανθίζω}},  {{t+|el|λουλουδίζω}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|ἀνθέω}}\n* Greenlandic: {{t|kl|sikkerneq}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|פָּרַח|tr=parákh}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|virágzik}}\n* Icelandic: {{t|is|blómstra}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|berkembang}},  {{t+|id|mekar}}\n* Interlingua: {{t|ia|florer}},  {{t|ia|florescer}}\n* Inuktitut: {{t|iu|erkpakpok}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|fiorire}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|咲く|tr=さく, saku}},  {{t+|ja|開花|tr=kaika suru|alt=開花する}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|피다}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|floreō}};  {{t|la|florescō}} {{qualifier|begin to blossom}};  {{t|la|efflorescō}} {{qualifier|break into bloom}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|ziedēt}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t|lt|žydėti}}\n* Luxembourgish: {{t|lb|bléien}},  {{t|lb|floréieren}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|цвета}}\n* Malayalam: {{t+|ml|പുഷ്പിക്കുക}}, {{t|ml|പൂവിടുക}}\n* Maltese: {{t|mt|iffjorixxa}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|pua}}\n* Marathi: {{t|mr|फूल}}\n* Middle English: {{t|enm|flouren}}\n* Norman: {{t|nrf|flieuthi}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|florir}}\n* Ojibwe: {{t|oj|baashkaabigwanii}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|kwitnąć}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|florir}},  {{t+|pt|florescer}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|înflori}}\n* Romansh: {{t|rm|flurir}},  {{t|rm|flureir}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|цвести́|impf}}\n* Sami:\n*: Northern Sami: {{t|se|lieđđut}}\n* Santali: {{t+|sat|ᱵᱟᱦᱟ}},  {{t|sat|ᱯᱷᱩᱞ}}\n* Sardinian: {{t|sc|fiorire}},  {{t|sc|fioriri}},  {{t|sc|florire}}\n* Sicilian: {{t+|scn|aggigghiari}},  {{t+|scn|ciuriri}},  {{t|scn|nzagarari}}\n* Slovak: {{t|sk|kvitnúť}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|cveteti}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|florecer}}, {{t|es|florescer}}\n* Swahili: {{t|sw|sitawi|alt=-sitawi}},  {{t+|sw|bariki|alt=-bariki}},  {{t+|sw|chanua|alt=-chaunua}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|blomma}}\n* Tagalog: {{t|tl|mamulaklak}}\n* Tamil: {{t+|ta|பூ}}\n* Telugu: {{t+|te|పుష్పించు}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|แย้ม|tr=yáem}},  {{t|th|แตกปลี|tr=dtààek bplee}}\n* Tonga (Zambia): {{t|toi|fulula}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|çiçeklenmek}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|цвісти́|impf}}, {{t+|uk|кві́тнути|impf}}\n* Unami: {{t|unm|òtaèwi}}\n* Urdu: {{t|ur|کھلنا|tr=khilnā}}\n* Uzbek: {{t+|uz|gul}}\n* Venetan: {{t|vec|fiorir}}\n* Volapük: {{t+|vo|florön}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|flori}}\n}}<!-- close multitrans -->\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col4|en\n|aflower\n|corpse flower\n|flower girl\n|flowerbed\n|flowerpot\n|flowery\n|passionflower\n|sunflower\n|wild flower,wildflower\n}}\n\n====Related terms====\n{{col4|en\n|fleur\n|flora,Flora\n|floret\n|florid\n|florist\n|floristics\n|inflorescence}}\n\n====See also====\n* [[:Category:Flowers]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{etymid|en|flows}} From {{affix|en|flow|-er|id2=agent noun}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|en|flow-er}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈfləʊə/|a=UK}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-flower2.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈfloʊɚ/|a=US}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|rare|especially|crosswording}} Something that [[flow]]s, such as a [[river]].\n#* '''1886–1890''', J. D. Rees, ''Narratives of Tours in India'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=PragpcesPogC&lpg=PA340&ots=-8E6Ptps8n&dq=%22swift%20flower%22%20water&pg=PA340#v=onepage&q=%22swift%20flower%22%20water&f=false page 340]:\n#*: Leaving the weavers’ village behind you, and crossing the sandy bed of the Vengavati or ‘Swift-'''flower''',’ which, however, contained not a drop of water, you reach the ancient Jain temple.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1888|author=John T. White|title=The Seventh Book of Cæsar’s Gallic War with a Vocabulary|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=5kkVAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22swift-flower%22&pg=PA224#v=onepage&q=%22swift-flower%22&f=false|page=224\n|passage=Rhŏdănus, i, m. ''The Rhodanus'' (now ''Rhone''); a river of Gaul [prob. a northern word, meaning “Swift-'''flower''' ''or'' Swift-passer”].}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1893|author=Arthur A. MacDonnell|title=A Sanskrit-English Dictionary|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=-P9SIJE2IvAC&lpg=PA340&ots=fZZprW61Hf&dq=%22swift%20flower%22%20river&pg=PA340#v=onepage&q=%22swift%20flower%22%20river&f=false|page=340\n|passage=sará-yu, ''f''. [swift '''flower''': √''sri''] ''N. of a river (in Oudh), in C. gnly.'' û.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1959|journal=Scottish Studies|volume=3-4|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=f5RnAAAAMAAJ&q=%22fast+flower%22+flows&dq=%22fast+flower%22+flows&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jClCVf3jCMGeNoOUgdgJ&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAw|page=92\n|passage=one that flows with force and speed; the ''fast '''flower'''''}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=24 August 2019|journal=Radio Times Crossword\n|passage=Bonnie partner with Scottish '''flower''' (5)  [as a clue for ''CLYDE'']}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* The term is used with this meaning almost exclusively in [[cryptic crossword]] clues, where it generally stands in for the name of a specific river.\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=eflorw|Fowler|Wolfer|flowre|fowler|reflow|wolfer}}\n\n{{cln|en|heteronyms}}\n{{C|en|Plant anatomy}}\n\n==Cebuano==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{unadapted borrowing|ceb|en|flower}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ceb-IPA|flawer}}\n* {{hyph|ceb|flow|er}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{ceb-noun|flówer|b=+}}\n\n# someone who is [[allow]]ed to [[participate]] in [[game]]s but cannot become [[it]]; usually a younger [[sibling]] of a [[player]] who may or may not fully grasp the [[mechanics]] of the game\n# {{lb|ceb|mahjong}} {{l|en|flower}} or [[season]] tile\n# {{lb|ceb|mahjong}} act of declaring and revealing a flower or season tile and in order drawing a replacement tile\n\n{{C|ceb|Games}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|flour}}"}}